The Canadians are
considering prosecution.

40:00.031 --> 40:02.400
He's ready to make
a statement implicating Birch.

40:02.400 --> 40:04.035
At Quantico, they call a case
this straightforward --

40:04.035 --> 40:05.604
Nobody cares.

40:05.604 --> 40:06.671
Of course not.
Why would they?

40:06.671 --> 40:09.074
Rookies always bring up
Quantico.

40:10.809 --> 40:12.644
Uh, do you need
something else?

40:13.578 --> 40:16.548
Let me know if you need
PDF backups of those.

40:16.548 --> 40:17.549
[Bryan] Will do.

40:17.549 --> 40:18.884
He is  right, though.

40:18.884 --> 40:20.886
This Birch thing's
a dunker.

40:22.721 --> 40:24.756
Dominique all day.

40:26.591 --> 40:28.927
Wilkins!

40:43.141 --> 40:45.877
So, tomorrow morning, when
the arrest warrant is issued,

40:45.877 --> 40:47.112
along with a search warrant,

40:47.112 --> 40:49.714
we meet near Birch's firm,
all right?

40:49.714 --> 40:52.017
[Bryan] You guys take him,
we take his records.

40:52.017 --> 40:53.885
Hey, quick question.
Alan.

40:53.885 --> 40:55.120
Are we
gonna handcuff him?

40:55.120 --> 40:56.488
Yeah, obviously.

40:56.488 --> 40:59.024
[man] What about the S.E.C.?
Should we alert them?

40:59.024 --> 41:00.158
We already have.

41:00.158 --> 41:01.159
[Terri] Press?

41:01.159 --> 41:02.627
Probably, all right?

41:02.627 --> 41:04.129
I mean, those news cameras

41:04.129 --> 41:07.065
just have a way of showing up
at the right time, don't they?

41:07.065 --> 41:08.567
[laughter]

41:08.567 --> 41:09.835
[man] So, we're gonna hit 'em
full-on, right?

41:09.835 --> 41:11.002
[Bryan] Yes.

41:11.002 --> 41:12.237
[echoing]
We'll get local law enforcement

41:12.237 --> 41:13.939
there on the perimeter,
but with the lights out.

41:13.939 --> 41:15.173
[laughter]

41:15.173 --> 41:19.010
[talking continues
indistinctly, echoes]

41:19.010 --> 41:21.913
[Bryan] All right,
any more questions?

41:21.913 --> 41:25.217
[talking continues
indistinctly, echoes]

41:25.217 --> 41:26.117
Bryan?

41:29.888 --> 41:31.957
Let's put a pin
in the arrest.

41:31.957 --> 41:32.691
Boss?

41:32.691 --> 41:34.159
Get Birch in here.

41:34.159 --> 41:35.560
It's time to settle.

41:35.560 --> 41:37.596
No, no. N-No way.

41:37.596 --> 41:40.498
We -- We have him dead to rights
on this trial.

41:40.498 --> 41:42.834
I'm first chair.
Then it's jail for this jamoke.

41:42.834 --> 41:45.036
We have him dead to rights,
so he'll fold quick,

41:45.036 --> 41:48.173
and then we get back to
what we were doing -- Axelrod.

41:48.173 --> 41:52.510
I'm not letting us follow
the riderless horse any longer.

41:52.510 --> 41:53.612
Wait.
Riderless h--

41:53.612 --> 41:55.780
Butch Cassidy
and the Sundance Kid.

41:55.780 --> 41:57.148
They were smart.

41:58.984 --> 42:01.786
They sent one of their horses
off in a different direction

42:01.786 --> 42:04.522
so the posse
would have to split up...

42:04.522 --> 42:06.892
get distracted.

42:06.892 --> 42:10.829
But this was
no ordinary posse.

42:10.829 --> 42:14.132
This was a super posse --
the  super posse.

42:14.132 --> 42:15.901
Mixed group
of superheroes --

42:15.901 --> 42:18.570
a sheriff,
a marshal, an Indian.

42:18.570 --> 42:20.105
"Native American."

42:21.106 --> 42:22.007
Sure.

42:22.007 --> 42:23.141
And the Cherokee --

42:23.141 --> 42:25.777
man, he could read
the depth of the impression

42:25.777 --> 42:28.780
the horse's hooves
made on rock.

42:28.780 --> 42:32.851
And when he realized they were
chasing a riderless horse...

42:34.085 --> 42:37.222
...they got right back
on Butch's trail.

42:37.222 --> 42:38.924
I remember now.

42:38.924 --> 42:40.859
I watched it with my dad

42:40.859 --> 42:43.828
on one of the Saturdays
he showed up.

42:43.828 --> 42:46.298
I didn't root
for the super posse.

42:46.298 --> 42:47.966
I rooted
for Butch and Sundance.

42:47.966 --> 42:49.968
Of course you did.
We all  did.

42:52.170 --> 42:54.873
But that's not who we are
anymore.

43:00.946 --> 43:03.982
[light piano music plays,
indistinct conversations]

43:07.352 --> 43:09.154
How are you, Bobby?

43:12.757 --> 43:14.693
Hey, Garth.

43:14.693 --> 43:15.827
Ken.

43:18.363 --> 43:20.098
I'd call you "Sir Ken"
out of respect

43:20.098 --> 43:22.367
for your advanced age
and your accomplishments,

43:22.367 --> 43:24.903
but, as much as you'd like it,
you were born in Chicago,

43:24.903 --> 43:26.838
and no one born there
was ever knighted.

43:26.838 --> 43:28.707
He would  like it
if we called him "sir."

43:28.707 --> 43:30.775
He is  that type.

43:30.775 --> 43:32.911
You are  that type, Ken.

43:32.911 --> 43:34.946
And then
what would we call you,  Axe?

43:34.946 --> 43:38.049
Oh, hell, Kenny, call me
whatever the fuck you want.

43:39.050 --> 43:42.187
[chair scrapes]

43:42.187 --> 43:45.056
Or better,
don't ever call me.

43:45.056 --> 43:46.925
You know the reason
why you should never call me?

43:46.925 --> 43:48.927
Because
you're a poacher, Ken,

43:48.927 --> 43:52.063
and guys like Garth and me,
we do not like poachers.

43:52.063 --> 43:53.398
Come drag a deer
off my land,

43:53.398 --> 43:55.133
see what the fuck
happens to you.

43:56.801 --> 43:59.804
Well, now that you've joined us,
let me ask you --

43:59.804 --> 44:01.139
how you doing?

44:01.139 --> 44:04.109
I'm gonna let you in
on something here, Garth.

44:04.109 --> 44:06.177
Hedge fund guys
only ask that question

44:06.177 --> 44:08.747
when they know
the other guy is running bad,

44:08.747 --> 44:10.949
which he thinks because
you are sitting with him.

44:10.949 --> 44:12.817
Oh, we're
just catching up.

44:12.817 --> 44:14.152
And you still
haven't answered.

44:14.152 --> 44:16.321
[Bobby] It's a "crush
the other guy" business.

44:16.321 --> 44:19.691
It's like "Highlander" --
there can be only one.

44:19.691 --> 44:23.028
[Bobby] I don't blame you, Ken.
I'd do the same thing.

44:23.995 --> 44:26.431
But I'm up 32% this year,

44:26.431 --> 44:29.401
which, from what I know
of your run-and-hide approach,

44:29.401 --> 44:32.904
is 30 points better than
what you are at Vista Verde.

44:32.904 --> 44:35.140
Well, you can call it
what you want,

44:35.140 --> 44:37.175
but I call it "careful."

44:37.175 --> 44:39.778
Risk-averse.

44:39.778 --> 44:41.379
When I opened my fund,

44:41.379 --> 44:43.448
I was very aware
of the responsibility

44:43.448 --> 44:45.750
that people like Garth
put in my hands,

44:45.750 --> 44:48.853
which is why
I hedge my investments.

44:48.853 --> 44:51.389
I protect the downside.

44:52.924 --> 44:55.226
I may not be
a rock star,

44:55.226 --> 44:57.095
but I'm still
plugging away,

44:57.095 --> 44:59.264
all these many years
later.

45:01.166 --> 45:02.934
Have fun
with your plugger.

45:04.169 --> 45:06.337
Can we step away
for a sec?

45:14.746 --> 45:16.181
I love
talking to you, Axe,

45:16.181 --> 45:18.817
and you made us
a shit ton of money, but...

45:18.817 --> 45:22.720
I need to keep things
nice and comfy --

45:22.720 --> 45:24.823
results and  optics.

45:24.823 --> 45:27.392
[Sykes] My job's
to spot a fund manager

45:27.392 --> 45:30.862
taking his eye off the ball
before he strikes out.

45:30.862 --> 45:32.363
That's what my members
count on.

45:32.363 --> 45:36.267
And they see someone like
Kenneth, dry ass that he is,

45:36.267 --> 45:39.437
as solid...

45:39.437 --> 45:42.107
part of the firmament.

45:42.107 --> 45:43.808
Sometimes
that's important.

45:44.876 --> 45:46.177
I hear you.

45:46.177 --> 45:50.081
And I know you hated
the headline in the newspaper.

45:50.081 --> 45:52.417
Do what you have to do.

45:52.417 --> 45:54.319
But I hope
that in the days to come,

45:54.319 --> 45:56.454
you see me
as part of that firmament.

45:58.523 --> 46:00.391
I think you will.

46:07.065 --> 46:08.533
[door closes]

46:10.468 --> 46:13.905
You've all seen
the evidence we've gathered

46:13.905 --> 46:16.207
regarding
your railroad trades.

46:16.207 --> 46:18.343
If we prevail at trial --

46:18.343 --> 46:20.078
which we're confident
we will --

46:20.078 --> 46:21.446
the federal sentencing
guidelines

46:21.446 --> 46:24.549
call for you
to serve 11 years.

46:26.851 --> 46:29.354
We understand that
you have young children.

46:29.354 --> 46:31.256
Well, maybe
they'll be out of college

46:31.256 --> 46:33.324
by the time
you're released.

46:33.324 --> 46:35.827
Maybe you can make it
to their weddings.

46:35.827 --> 46:39.531
[Bryan] But like we told
your lawyers,

46:39.531 --> 46:42.233
we're willing to forgo that
for a quick plea --

46:42.233 --> 46:43.401
an admission of guilt,

46:43.401 --> 46:47.839
a forfeiture money judgment
of $386 million.

46:47.839 --> 46:50.408
[Chuck] As well as the voluntary
shuttering of your fund

46:50.408 --> 46:53.411
and conversion of it
to a family office.

46:53.411 --> 46:55.446
You'll no longer handle
any  outside money.

46:55.446 --> 46:57.882
I can get the S.E.C. in here
right now to do that

46:57.882 --> 46:58.816
if you don't agree.

47:01.119 --> 47:03.021
So, settlement or trial?

47:04.556 --> 47:06.824
We're prepared to fight this
for as long as we --

47:06.824 --> 47:08.293
I...

47:08.293 --> 47:10.929
came here today
to take a deal.

47:11.996 --> 47:14.065
I don't want
to go to jail.

47:15.567 --> 47:18.369
Wise choice, Mr. Birch.

47:18.369 --> 47:19.470
Stay in the light.

47:19.470 --> 47:22.607
You won't be getting
a chance like this again.

47:33.885 --> 47:35.220
This doesn't
have to be over.

47:35.220 --> 47:37.288
I'm actually relieved
we settled.

47:37.288 --> 47:39.257
[door closes]

47:49.167 --> 47:51.302
[cellphone chimes]

48:10.888 --> 48:12.156
[groans]

48:13.891 --> 48:15.026
Comfortable?

48:16.227 --> 48:19.097
For the first time
all fucking day.

48:19.097 --> 48:22.033
Well, I have someone
coming in here soon,

48:22.033 --> 48:24.936
and they might be a little
freaked to see their boss...

48:29.374 --> 48:32.243
I just came by to say
"thank you" and "sorry" --

48:32.243 --> 48:34.012
two words
I don't say very often.

48:34.012 --> 48:37.482
So it's handled
with Victor?

48:37.482 --> 48:40.351
You nailed it --
on every count.

48:40.351 --> 48:42.053
And he got paid.

48:42.053 --> 48:45.657
I used everything I knew about
him to make him capitulate.

48:45.657 --> 48:47.392
That's why
I asked you to go.

48:47.392 --> 48:49.494
[Wendy]
You know why I went?

48:49.494 --> 48:51.529
For you.

48:53.631 --> 48:56.601
You and I...

48:56.601 --> 48:58.436
we've never
let each other down

48:58.436 --> 49:00.438
in all these years.

49:00.438 --> 49:02.273
And I wasn't
about to start

49:02.273 --> 49:05.109
because you  acted
like that never happened.

49:08.613 --> 49:11.015
Cut me out again...

49:11.015 --> 49:12.283
and I'm gone.

49:14.152 --> 49:16.054
I know.

49:16.054 --> 49:18.189
[cellphone vibrates]

49:21.392 --> 49:22.994
[cellphone chimes]

49:27.098 --> 49:28.299
I won't.

49:43.181 --> 49:44.382
Ellis Eads.

49:44.382 --> 49:47.318
We are honored to share this
privilege with you, Mr. Axelrod.

49:47.318 --> 49:48.686
With you, too,
Mrs. Axelrod.

49:48.686 --> 49:50.988
There's no sharing, Ellis.
It's Axelrod Hall now.

49:50.988 --> 49:52.523
No. Of course.
We understand.

49:52.523 --> 49:54.192
You think  you do.

49:56.694 --> 49:58.629
Now, I saw
that when I came in here,

49:58.629 --> 50:00.264
you don't remember me,
Chad.

50:00.264 --> 50:02.300
I know who you are.

50:02.300 --> 50:06.070
But you don't
actually remember.

50:06.070 --> 50:07.004
We've met before.

50:08.740 --> 50:11.642
I caddied at The Spoon
when I was a kid.

50:11.642 --> 50:14.345
It was
the perfect summer job.

50:14.345 --> 50:16.114
I carried
your grandfather's bag

50:16.114 --> 50:17.515
quite a few times.

50:17.515 --> 50:18.783
Your  bag, too, Chad,

50:18.783 --> 50:20.385
in the summer
after middle school.

50:21.652 --> 50:24.789
How funny
that we all end up here.

50:24.789 --> 50:26.691
[Bobby]
Now, here's the thing.

50:26.691 --> 50:29.093
A lot of numbers
have been thrown around --

50:29.093 --> 50:32.797
100 for the naming rights,
25 for your name to come down.

50:32.797 --> 50:36.734
But there is one  number
that really matters to me --

50:36.734 --> 50:39.604
16.

50:39.604 --> 50:40.805
And we'll see

50:40.805 --> 50:42.774
if you still think
it's funny, Chad.

50:42.774 --> 50:46.644
[Bobby] $16 is what
a caddy got paid for a loop.

50:46.644 --> 50:50.681
Four hours of humping bags,
smelling sour cigars,

50:50.681 --> 50:52.617
and watching all of you
lie to each other

50:52.617 --> 50:55.486
about your golf scores
in the 95-degree heat,

50:55.486 --> 50:58.322
but I was happy
for the job.

50:58.322 --> 50:59.690
[Bobby] That 16 bucks --

50:59.690 --> 51:01.325
and I would do two loops
a day,

51:01.325 --> 51:04.228
so it was $32 on a Saturday,
$32 on a Sunday.

51:04.228 --> 51:06.697
By the end of the weekend,
I'd have 64 bucks.

51:06.697 --> 51:07.732
16 weekends,

51:07.732 --> 51:10.635
Memorial to Labor Day,
$1,024.

51:10.635 --> 51:12.837
[Lara]
That was his spending money
for the entire year.

51:12.837 --> 51:15.440
He'd stretch it out
until the next summer.

51:15.440 --> 51:17.275
Pretty much.

51:18.376 --> 51:20.411
Until --

51:20.411 --> 51:22.380
and you were there
for this, Chad --

51:22.380 --> 51:25.383
your grandfather asked me
to read a putt on three.

51:25.383 --> 51:28.085
It was a left-to-right leaker,
and I told him so.

51:28.085 --> 51:30.388
I'd seen the putt
all summer long.

51:30.388 --> 51:34.125
He closed the face, pulled it,
missed it by a foot.

51:34.125 --> 51:35.593
You laughed at him.

51:35.593 --> 51:37.395
[Bobby] You made fun
of his eyesight.

51:37.395 --> 51:40.097
And he turned to me,

51:40.097 --> 51:43.167
and he fired me
right there.

51:43.167 --> 51:47.271
Not from the round,
but from the club.

51:47.271 --> 51:50.441
Now, I needed that $16,
but he didn't give a shit.

51:50.441 --> 51:52.677
Because he was embarrassed
to have missed a putt

51:52.677 --> 51:53.878
in front of his grandson.

51:53.878 --> 51:55.246
Are you saying
we are here

51:55.246 --> 51:56.547
because
of that ancient bullshit?

51:56.547 --> 51:58.483
That's right!

51:58.483 --> 52:00.351
16.

52:00.351 --> 52:02.520
